n and organised by the Education Department at Tate Britain and the Paul Mellon Centre for British Art. An important part of my paper explored the relationship in the 1950's between sculptor Ivor Roberts-Jones and Helen Lessore - owner of the Beaux Arts Gallery. My paper also touched on Lessore's efforts to promote the work of some of Roberts-Jones's British/European contemporaries such as Daphne Hardy, Elizabeth Frink, Frank Dobson, Marino Marini and Giacomo Manzu within the context of her active promotion of the so-called 'Kitchen Sink' group of oil painters. At the beginning of the Conference Roberts-Jones was not an artist known to the majority of the speakers and to the audience. However, by its end, from comments made by fellow speakers and some members of the audience, it was clear that they now saw the sculptor in a new and much more positive light. They were also more prepared to entertain the thought that the Kitchen Sink movement was not restricted to painting but did indeed possess a lively and thought-provoking sculptural dimension.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Postgraduate students</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.tate.org.uk/what's-on/tate-britain/conference</gtr:url><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Public Lecture on Ivor Roberts-Jones and his Statues of Sir Winston Churchill for the Institute of Art History, Budapest</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>B8A2A357-0014-402C-B58E-DFD61894D6C7</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Lengthy discussion after my lecture as to status of public sculpture in Hungary today; what should be done, if anything, to safeguard public sculpture produced during the country's discredited Communist era (1945-90) as well as what problems may arise from the contemporary commissioning of public sculpture by still controversial fig