Also the publication of a revised and expanded brochure by HMSO: 'The Attlee Memorial Statue in the House of Commons'.

Part of my research for this project has also been used for a section in my forthcoming study of Winston Churchill in British Art c. 1900 to the present day which comments how Ivor Roberts-Jones depicted Churchill in sculpture in London's Parliament Square (1973) and in New Orleans, USA (1977).

And factual material underpinning:
One exhibition at the National Museum of Wales ('The Double Edge: The Portrait Sculpture of Ivor Roberts-Jones', December 2013-May 2014)
and
Two displays; one focussing on his Whitehall Statue of Field Marshal Viscount Slim (Henry Moore Institute, Leeds, April-June 2014) and the second on his statue of Clement Attlee in the Members Lobby of the House of Commons (Portcullis House, Palace of Westminster, October-December 2014).

Also for a display at the Fordingbridge Museum, Hampshire, focussing on the bronze statue of painter Augustus John which Roberts-Jones made for the town in c. 1966-67 and which was unveiled in October 1967. The display opened at the end of March 2015 and is located at the entrance to the Museum's first floor. It consists of four illustrated panels exploring: John's connection with the town (from 1927 he lived nearby at Fryan's Court); the career of Ivor Roberts-Jones (selected to make the statue in spring 1964); the story of the statue's commission and, finally, why the statue's current location is different to its originally selected site. Text and imagery for the panels was provided by myself. The production of the panels was funded by money from my original AHRC Roberts-Jones Award set aside for this specific purpose.

Plus the content of five public lectures; to the Institute of Art History, Hungarian Academy of Science, Budapest (October 2012); the Czech and Slovak Association of Great Britain (April 2013); the Society of Portrait Sculptors, London (May 2013); the Fifth Annual Sir Kyffin Williams Lecture at Highgate School, London (February 2015) and for Fordingbridge Museum Trust, Fordingbridge, Hampshire (March 2015).

